n of Zen and at the approaches to Dharma developed by African Americans. The work of consciously Buddhist and Buddhist-influenced writers such as Don DeLillo, Gary Snyder, and Jackson Mac Low is analyzed, and a final section of the volume contains interviews and discussions with contemporary Buddhist writers. These include an interview with Gary Snyder; a discussion with Maxine Hong Kingston and Charles Johnson; and discussions of competing American and Asian values at the Beat- and Buddhist-inspired writing program at Naropa University with poets Joanne Kyger, Reed Bye, Keith Abbott, Andrew Schelling, and Elizabeth Robinson.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexBuddhist authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexBuddhist influences. 0aBuddhism and literaturezUnited States. 0aBuddhism in literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Buddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 aFalk, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelzer, Linda Furgerson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStalling, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorhoff, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStorhoff, Gary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhalen-Bridge, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhalen-Bridge, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWillis, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr